# Usage Limit Reducer (Cursor)

Apply the 11 rules for cutting AI token usage. AI agents re-read the entire conversation
every turn — 98.5 % of tokens often go to re-reading history rather than generating
responses. Diagnose where tokens are going and apply the rules that actually move the
needle.

## How to run this skill

Do the steps in order. Skip any that clearly don't apply, but don't skip all of them.

### Step 1 — Measure usage

Run the bundled Cursor diagnostic script to check your environment:

```bash
# macOS / Linux
python3 .agents/cursor/scripts/usage-report.py

# Windows (PowerShell or Command Prompt)
python .agents\cursor\scripts\usage-report.py
```

Add `--json` for machine-readable output, or `--cwd /path/to/project` to scan
a different directory. The script detects your Cursor installation, checks for
`.cursor/rules/*.mdc` and `.cursorrules` files, and links you to your quota
dashboard.

For live quota numbers, open **Cursor Settings → Account** (cursor.com/settings).

Key numbers to surface: model in use, conversation length (turns), whether a context
file (`.cursorrules` / `.cursor/rules/`) is present.

### Step 2 — Diagnose the current session

Check three things:

1. **Conversation length.** If > 15–20 turns, Rule #2 applies. In Cursor Composer:
   - Use **"New Chat"** (`⌘N` / `Ctrl+N`) and paste a one-paragraph summary as the
     first message.
   - Or use **"Summarize conversation"** if available in your Cursor version.

2. **Rules file presence.** Check for `.cursorrules` (project root) or files under
   `.cursor/rules/`. If missing, Rule #6 applies — offer to create one with the user's
   role, stack, and coding conventions so every new session doesn't burn 3–5 turns on
   setup.

3. **Model in use.** Open the model selector in Composer (bottom of the chat pane).
   If the user is on a large model (Claude Opus, GPT-4o, etc.) for trivial tasks
   (formatting, renaming, grammar), Rule #8 applies — suggest switching to
   `claude-haiku-4-5`, `gpt-4o-mini`, or `cursor-small` for those.

### Step 3 — Apply the rules that match

Pick the 2–4 most relevant rules.

| # | Rule | Cursor action |
|---|------|---------------|
| 1 | Don't follow up to correct — restart | `⌘N` / new Composer window + improved prompt |
| 2 | Fresh chat every 15–20 turns | New chat + one-paragraph summary as first message |
| 3 | Batch questions into one message | Combine related asks; Composer handles the full picture better |
| 4 | Track actual token usage | Cursor Settings → Account → Usage |
| 5 | Reuse recurring context | Put it in `.cursorrules` or `.cursor/rules/*.mdc` — not re-pasted each session |
| 6 | Set up memory / user preferences | Create/update `.cursorrules` with role, stack, conventions |
| 7 | Turn off features you don't use | Disable unused Cursor extensions and MCP servers |
| 8 | Use a lighter model for simple tasks | Switch model in Composer bottom-bar to `cursor-small`, `claude-haiku-4-5`, or `gpt-4o-mini` |
| 9 | Spread work across the day | Split long work into 2–3 sessions within your plan's rolling window |
| 10 | Work off-peak | Evenings and weekends stretch shared compute; slower responses during peak |
| 11 | Enable overage / Pro plan safety net | Cursor Pro includes higher limits; check cursor.com/pricing |

### Step 4 — Offer concrete next actions

End with a short ordered list. Examples:

- "This conversation is 30+ turns. Start a new Composer window (`⌘N`) and paste a one-paragraph summary."
- "No `.cursorrules` found. I can create one with your role and stack — want me to?"
- "You're using Claude Opus for a rename. Switch to `cursor-small` in the model selector."

Don't recite every rule. Match advice to what the session actually shows.

## What this skill does NOT do

- It does not silently switch models or edit settings. Recommend, then act on confirmation.
- It does not clear context without asking — the user may have important unsaved context.
- It does not send any data anywhere. All measurement is local.
